ize indeterminate, but only for a moment. Flaring with light from its center, it seemed to grow and dilate, the spark contained within seeming to grow brighter but shed no light as the ring stretched and thinned ever further.<br><br>Then the shock came, the spark flaring as something passed through, but not through the far side of  the construct. <br><br>Like a titan rising from the earth, a giant of the stars slipped through the portal ring, massive bulk quiescent as it was wreathed by the energy of transference.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *<br><br>&quot;Soh'tak!&quot; Ra'Kolan shouted into the darkness, senses tingling as he strained to identify any tangible effects of the transfer. As always, there were none but the split-second glimpse of the threshold, a ghostly wall sweeping down the length of the ship as it passed from place to place.<br><br>Around him, Law-of-Anarchy rose from slumber to hunting-status, the massive ship signalling wakefulness with a change of the battle-drums. Cocking one pointed ear to better catch the tempo, Ra'Kolan felt the calm of relief wash away under the steady march of the computer-generated war song.<br><br>&quot;Ju'ka, status?&quot; He barked, grasping the textured arms of his command couch to give himself a sense of control where he knew he had none.<br><br>&quot;The temporary point will disappear with the passing of the comet in a moment. I see no sign of alarm from any planetary defenses.  The Heresy-of-Innovation is present and Instrument-of-Chaos is finished shifting... now.&quot; The sensing-officer responded, his niche of consoles the only ones on the bridge remaining powered, and only at half.<br><br>&quot;Te'va. Let us proceed, then.&quot; He mused, knowing well they were already underway, drifting at transition-speed toward target. It simply felt better to fill the empty air with noise, but Shipself responded nonetheless, perhaps also feeling the need to fill the air. Machine perhaps, but no less a being, no less a Taiyan-Kerrahi in soul to be birthed by forge and nanite than the coupling flesh of parents.<br><br>&quot;I stand ready, Ra'Ko'lan! Our charges lie eager in their assault pods and aerospace craft, waiting only to be loosed on the poor pitiable bastards below us. Weapons and defenses remain well prepared but unpowered.&quot; The air responded in a melodious but echoing voice, the Ship-self flavoring its' words with confidence and agression as it made report.<br><br>&quot;Engagement farpoint reached. No response whatsoever.&quot; Sensors pronounced eagerly.<br><br>Cat-slit pupils glowing in the red-lit darkness of the command deck, it seemed every Taiyan aboard bared their canines in a feral, predatory grin at that announcement...<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *<br><br>Aboard the Instrument-of-Chaos the sensation was similar, but more acute. The tempo of the battlehymn was faster, matching the pulses of the crew as they imagined the predatory lines of their ship, blind and unpowered though it was, slipping silently between the bulks of the slower-moving battle carriers.<br><br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Chu'koleh sha'ha, mweh kell.&quot; </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->One of the Kerrahi intoned, making the ritual left-to-right, top-to-bottom, inverted L shape of a war blessing in the air before his face, and then bowing his head and repeating the gesture over his console to renforce his luck with the luck of the ship.<br><br>The Taiyan near him held no faith in such superstition, but all restrained their cynicysm, and a scattered few born beyond the portal mirrored the gesture, while others gleaned their own reassurance fingering trophy-necklaces or Marks. Many others recited the Law of Ascendance. A single thought that could result in the extermination of an entire colony. <br><br>And a just penalty for a hienous crime.<br><br>&quot;Nearpoint reached. Reactor to power, passing stasis point now. Aerospace-fighters charging and readying for release. Point-defense-ready. Offensive-Systems ready. Sensors prepared to activate, scan-and-acquire pattern ready. Target resolution vectors and probable course adjustments calculated.&quot;  The shipself announced, the battle music mixing with more drumbeats and tempos, pulsing deeper and louder as each system added its' status to the cadence.<br><br>&quot;All systems to power!&quot; Ta'Reja commanded, his voice the thunderclap that triggered an avalanche of action.<br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Gunnery online!&quot;<br>&quot;Point Defense online!&quot;<br>&quot;Contact aquired, firing single-shot seeker munitions from tubes one and three!&quot;<br>&quot;Contacts aquired, five inbound interceptor-fighters, Nau'kel size or lighter...&quot;<br>&quot;Thrusters online, inertial decoupler engaged. Engineering straight green.&quot;<br>&quot;Reactor at nominal, ready for combat power-load! Ninety percent now...&quot;<br>&quot;Incoming volley, displacement singularities tracking and defending at nominal...&quot;<br></i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>As the whirlwind grew, Ta'Reja relaxed into his armature, bringing up the interface. Around him, the armature projection field blotted out the bridge, replacing it with a view of Outside. Ticks and whorls more felt than seen became his universe, flowing motions of his hands stroking and gesturing in the computer-projected ether silently translating to hundreds of directives to as many parts of his great ship. Slight movements of his fingers drew turrets from their blisters on the hull and oriented them on the incoming fightercraft like a piper entrancing a cobra from its den. <br><br>The hull of the ship seemed to vibrate as cannons opened fire, rapid-firing plasma beams and magnetic hyperacellerators sweeping a narrow path through the blackness with imperceptible viciousness, lancing out to sear the incoming fighters. The tempo of the war-song rose, drumbeats synchronized with reload/recycle times, the weaponsfire a symphony, a pulse, the song of death and war as the ship shook and jerked like a living beast as the salvo vented. Then it grew quiet, it's rage spent and the enemy passed. The enourmous energy discharges of the plasma and tremendous impact forces of the gauss projectiles had left only floating drops of molten metal and ceramic, drifting into to the blackness of empty space. The battlehymn slowed momentarily for their passing.<br><br>Silvered teardrops spinning in the dark void as the predatory shape of the Chaos slipped past the tumbling corpses, as uncaring as a razorfish as it passed the twisted wreckage of it's former prey and continued toward the spinning orb that was its intended target.<br><br>The battle was joined.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *<br><br>Watching carefully as the pips denoting turrets flashed from sullen yellow back to eager blue, Ta'Reja gestured their fire arcs to cover the ship completely, mortaring the chinks between the shielding displacement fields with the lighter gimballed cannon, while also focusing heavier weapons outward, to intercept threats before they could close to strike.<br><br>&quot;Ready skip-torpedos!&quot; He muttered aloud, tapping the empty space before the projection of their ship, directing the powerful but high-emission active sensor webs sweep the designated space. Like nighttime insects revealed by a searchlight, a cluster of traces appeared, and at his barked command the ship shuddered and the ventral launchers spat their offspring into the blackness.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *<br><br>Like newborn sea creatures, searching for a parent to suckle, the torpdoes tumbled from the launch canals of the Instrument-of-Chaos, seeming seemed to hang for a moment and gather their bearings as their inertia kept pace with the Instrument-of-Chaos. Then, resolving their targets, sped toward their victims on pillars of plasma flame.<br><br>Streaking into the darkness, several of the missiles suddenly went dead. The flames quenched, and minute masking fields engaged. They simply disappeared, even as plasma and particle beams lanced their former positions, trying to intercept them with no avail.<br><br>But safely within the masking-fields, the antimatter-warhead torpedos engaged their tracking drives- miniaturized inertial decouplers such as on their long gone parent ship. Silently, the decouplers diverted the missiles inertia, slewing them clear of the chaff bursts, running their downloaded sensor data through predictive algorithms. Then, one missile decloaked, sending forth a loud electromagnetic pulse, and dove forward at the targets.<br><br>Immediately, laser and point-defense cannon tore it to shreds. To little avail, as the warhead shielding failed. Antimatter and matter erupted into a mutispectral flash of heat and light, so great a torrent of energy that it burned active sensors and eyes alike, and stripped away the masking fields on the remaining torpedos.<br><br>Unfortunately, their targets were blinded, and the torpedos had no need of their own sensors anymore. The pulse of the first ship had illuminated their prey, allowing them to passively aquire without revealing themselves.<br><br>And so they struck, and ships evaporated in the hellish fires of antiparticle anihliation. Many of the first explosions detonated other missiles, but only one explosion would have been enough detonating in the midst of the blinded and crippled fleet, mere thousands of kilometers apart, and the fractricide only ensured there would be nothing larger than a speck left to impede the approaching troopships.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;Insertion corridor clear!&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Sensors screamed, risking an active-detection pulse during the explosions.<br><br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Ready for orbital bombardment! All hands stand ready for assault manouvering!&quot; </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->Ta'reja screamed in response, firing the combat drives for the first time since transition. <br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Like the roar of a roused demon, the shrill booming screech of the plasma torches filled the pressure spaces, the entire ship vibrating from their fury as tons of hyperplasma was jetted and diffused from the stern and belly of the ship, hurling it into a slingshot trajectory around the planet while pointing the most powerful powerful spinal and dorsal weapons down at the target. <br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Immediately upon assuming bombardment orientation, the bridge lights increased from the dim red of battle to clean yellow-white light, and gunnery rang with barked orders in battle speech and common.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Fire ranging volley.&quot; The gunnery-leader boomed, the space around his command armature filled with a targeting map of the surface and the numerous crosshairs of the surface-attack capable weapons.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp With noiseless flares of light and energy, the <br>Instrument of Chaos shuddered and released a barrage onto the surface dwellers below.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Adjust for atmospherics and prepare for full bombardment!&quot; The gunnery-leader shouted to his charges, straining against his seat-straps as he roared orders and shifted his armature from station to station with such force it seemed it would snap.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Gunnery, anti-emplacement saturation fire. All dorsal batteries!&quot; Ta'reja shouted, in accord with the deathmaster gunner. <br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Once more the ship shook, this time a prolonged rocking as what seemed round, harmless drops rained down to the suface like fat rain, bursting with harmless splashes on the green globe below. In truth, however, gigajoules of energized plasma were lancing forth from the Instrument-of-Chaos every second, thirty charged-plasma cannon vomiting forth wave after wave of destruction at the surface, methodically eradicating the fledgeling antiaerospace defenses of the world below, the harmless 'splashes' actually rock-hard shockwaves of compressed, superheated air laced with shattered debreis.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Retrothrusting! Stand by to release insertion vessels!&quot; Ta'reja informed his bridge, unconsciously wrestling the intangible holographic controls of his ship as though it were resisting him with the might of a roped Akila-Kila.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Heresy-of-Innovation and Law-of-Anarchy readying for drop orbit. Report all systems to Blue Light status. Repeat, Blue Light. Commencing drop deployment.&quot; Communications announced, changing the hue of the glowing status panels across the bridge from cream-white Ortillery status to the light blue strobe of drop stations.<br><br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp *<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Remind me again why we chose 'Crash-Landing' as the designation of our vessel, &quot; Koba complained sarcastically, slamming his lanky, red-brown Kerrahi self back against the bulkhead of the Ragnarok dropship with sufficient force to engage the restraint clamps and secure his powerarmor in place.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Shut up, male.&quot; Serra'ki, Kajuka-Ranag and Kajuka-Nemera responded in chorus, similarly filinging themselves against the claustrophobic walls of the assault transport. Secured, all three Taiyan relaxed and hung limply from the clamps, enjoying the strange lack of localized pressure that came from being suspended by their power-armor as they checked lucky tokens and emblems on their suits.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Serra'ki took it one step further. Her helmet open despite the regulations against it during combat conditions, she busily anointed her facial Marks with the sap from a crushed termaka berry. Millenia of superstitious lore and some ancient but well-documented occurances said that termaka could react with darksteel-ink tatoos and positively affect the wearer, but Serra was the only Taiyan Kajuka on the Instrument-of-Chaos to honor the practice. After critically examining the resultant smears of sap, she snapped her helmet shut and rolled the pulped rind between the armored fingers of her right hand.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Why do we even let B'channi order us around? She is a secondrank, after all.&quot; The Bweth-Koh Kerrah argued despairingly.<br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>&quot;I said shut up, male! You'll never truly outrank B'channi. She's a female, and you're a male, and so you'll <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  always </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->rank after her.&quot; Serra responded mockingly, bouncing the berry off the Kerrah's helmet visor.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp  Unfazed, the support trooper continued his cynical monologue. &quot;Just think- our sister ship is the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Controlled-Fall!</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Doesn't that seem a bit more... hmm, how to put this... I don't know, reassuring?!&quot;<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Lit'tle cow'ar'd! At lea't we are not t'board the Near-Miss!&quot; R'djag jeered, coming up the hatch ramp in his full Kjho Dhjengha battlesuit. The Korluth paused in the threshold, noticing that his companions had not yet boarded. Even with the massive girth of the Korluth support trooper recessed in the large support-weapons niche, loading any other armored troopers became a difficult exercise in gymnastics everyone was willing to forgo in favor of patience. Even during a battle drop. <br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Fortunately, Ta'Kjass scampered up the hatch, followed closely by the slithering tangle of arms that was their Mw'juma scout, Rhyekki. Both clamped in before anyone could issue a complaint about their tardiness.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Grunting as he squeezed himself into the final berth like a cork in the rectum of a fish (what a lovely metaphor, Serra'ki noted wryly), R'djag triggered the hatch control, sliding the half-meter of armor plate over their only exit.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp From now until the drop point, their lives depended on the pilot, the Kajuka-Kerra B'channi. <br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Ka-ju-ka.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> What a strange term in the Common. Before-from-childhood. Or tankmeat, as they themselves, as well as others, often jokingly referred to them. Often artificially engineered, usually gestated for between three and fifteen years in a life support pod, and fed sensory data through nanite-constructed pathways literally integrated into their brains, Kajuka were symbolic of the Taiyan way.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp With a lurch, the dropship began to move. Massive servocranes outside were shunting their transport to one of the two main launchers of the Instrument-of-Chaos.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The Assault Destroyer was decidedly not a carrier-ship, and the inertial retrograde/magnetic induction launchers mostly served as plasma-stream accelerators and gauss cannon barrels, but they could nonetheless launch and recover internal fightercraft and dropships.<br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Still, literally being shot out of cannon, and a combat weapon cannon rather than a dedicated ship-launcher, was not reassuring, even when she linked to the external sensor web with her neural interface. <br><br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Serra'ki<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> , she reflected. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Serra-bor</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, the order-syllable at the end of her name, like all females, but denoting something unnatural. Once, the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> 'ki</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> had meant abnormality of birth. Rarely, there would be the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> 'kih</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> 'keh</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of first-twin and second-twin, but <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> 'kii</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> held the lifelong stigma of a forced birth, be it from very early labor or ceasarian from a dying mother.<br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>But now, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> 'ki</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> was honorable, even worthy of respect and envy by common <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> 'ra</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> 'ta</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> 'ka</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. Neural interfacing had to be done early in childhood and under strictly controlled conditions, and thus was only possible for those whose birthyears were sacrificed to become Kajuka.  <br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>Beside her, Ranag and Nemera were relaxed, trading infomation with their mentors Mejiki and Kolreijj, artificial sentiences that had served as reality, parent, and conscience during their decade in the tanks.<br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>In that, she was grateful she was Serra'ki. Better abnormal and with a family than the loneliness-in-numbers that was the lot of a full Kajuka. Her mother deserved respect for allowing the medicants to transfer her from womb-of-flesh to womb-of-steel, never to experience each other's touch until she was almost in her second year of growth.<br>&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>But now... Now she was the epitome of the Juka warrior. The old teachings that stressed the synergy of physical coordination and discipline, the li